   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-PUTIN (Moscow) _ A man-in-the-news profile of Vladimir
Putin. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   REHNQUIST-REPORT (Washington) _ Chief Justice William Rehnquist
surveyed the state of the federal judiciary and pronounced himself
quite pleased. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GM-PRECEPT (Detroit) _ With hundreds of millions of dollars of
private and federal research work behind it, the General Motors
Precept, an experimental model to be introduced here on Jan. 9, is
probably the most expensive car ever built. But it is still a lot
of car for the money. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo and graphic are being sent to NYT photo/graphic
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NEW-JARGON (Undated) _ Trying to keep abreast of high-tech
terminology might seem, to use Silicon Valley lingo, to be WOMBAT
duty _ a waste of money, brains and time. But those who have never
heard of HTML are probably condemned to spend their lives offline,
and investors who don't understand EBITDAM might think profits
still move stock prices. It's time for a glossary of technobabble.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Looking at a century of stocks. By Floyd
Norris.
</P>
