   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday, 01/01/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Jan. 1, 2000 -- RUN-BEAMON-FAMILY-2 -- Naomi
Beamon, who died shortly after this photograph with her son, Bob,
was taken. Finding out the truth about his past has helped Beamon,
the record-setting long jumper during the 1968 Olympics, live in
the present. In his recently published autobiography, ``The Man Who
Could Fly'' (Genesis Press), Beamon describes how, at age 35, he
finally summoned the courage to confront his grandmother about a
lifetime of things left unsaid. Only then did he discover he had
been lied to. (Don Hogan Charles/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Jan. 1, 2000 -- RUN-BEAMON-FAMILY-1 -- Bob
Beamon, 53, and his wife, Milana, left, listen to his great-aunt,
Emmie King, who wanted to raise him. Finding out the truth about
his past has helped Beamon, the record-setting long jumper during
the 1968 Olympics, live in the present. In his recently published
autobiography, ``The Man Who Could Fly'' (Genesis Press), Beamon
describes how, at age 35, he finally summoned the courage to
confront his grandmother about a lifetime of things left unsaid.
Only then did he discover he had been lied to. (Don Hogan
Charles/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Jan. 1, 2000 -- -HYPE-MILLENNIUM -- Edward
Woodyard, a screenwriter from Armonk, N.Y., in a room at the
Marriot Marquis in Times Square, which he reserved for the
millenium celebration 16 years ago. With him is his wife Nancy. The
Marriot was only a half-finished skeleton of steel and concrete
when he made the plans. ``2000 was worth the wait,'' he says.'' I
was almost speechless. I don't have words for it.'' (Jeffery A.
Salter/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Jan. 1, 2000 -- LEGALIZING-MARIJUANA -- Ethan
A. Nadelmann, director of the Lindesmith Center, a drug policy
center set up in New York with money donated by the billionaire
George Soros. Nadelmann calls the war on drugs a ``fundamental
evil.'' ``There never has been a drug-free society,'' says
Nadelmann. ``We must learn how to live with drugs so they cause the
least possible harm and the best possible good.'' (Vincent
Laforet/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Jan 1, 2000 -- MACY'S-WINDOW-WEDDING -- Tracy
Crinion and Greg Nahas of Hoboken, N.J., embarce after getting
married in one of Macy's 34th Street windows on New Year's Day. The
wedding was first prize in an essay contest. The couple also won a
trip to Aruba for their honeymoon. (Chris Maynard/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYY5) NEW YORK -- Jan. 1, 2000 -- NEWYEARS-ARIEL-FLOATER -- As
up to two million people packed midtown Manhattan on Friday to ring
in a new century, lights from buildings all around Times Square and
up and down Broadway provided quite a show for spectators from all
around the world. (Ozier Muhammad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) PALO ALTO, Calif. -- Jan. 1, 2000 -- Y2K-WHAT-PROBLEMS-2
-- Deb Leavitt, seated, and Carson Kan monitoring Hewlett-Packard's
computer systems at a company command center on over New Year's.
Although few problems were reported worldwide, many computer
experts warn that significant problems could still emerge in the
months to come if less critical or less frequently used computers,
programs or microchips belatedly become confused. And little of the
world's vast array of financial and office computing systems will
face real-world Year 2000 conditions until business resumes Monday.
(Peter DaSilva/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) PLANO, Texas -- Jan. 1, 2000 -- SUB-Y2K-WHAT-PROBLEMS-1
-- Computer monitoring centers like the one at Electronic Data
Systems in Plano, reported few problems as they kept watch over New
Year's. Yet many computer experts warn that significant problems
could still emerge in the months to come if less critical or less
frequently used computers, programs or microchips belatedly become
confused. And little of the world's vast array of financial and
office computing systems will face real-world Year 2000 conditions
until business resumes Monday. (Mark Graham/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) PLANO, Texas -- Jan. 1, 2000 -- Y2K-WHAT-PROBLEMS-1 --
Computer monitoring centers like the one at Electronic Data Systems
in Plano, reported few problems as they kept watch over New Year's.
Yet many computer experts warn that significant problems could
still emerge in the months to come if less critical or less
frequently used computers, programs or microchips belatedly become
confused. And little of the world's vast array of financial and
office computing systems will face real-world Year 2000 conditions
until business resumes Monday. (Mark Graham/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) OSH, Kyrgyzstan -- Jan. 1, 2000 -- KYRGYZSTAN-EPIC -- A
girl at a school in Osh, Kyrgyzstan, recites lines from the epic
poem about Manas. The poem has been handed down orally for
generations by Manaschis, masters of recitation who chant it at
festivals and other gatherings, and has now become a moral and
ideological text for the nation's youth. Because there has never
been an authoritative text, each Manaschi can weave in original
lines, and even episodes and characters. The greatest of them are
revered as prodigious creators in their own right. (Staton R.
Winter/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
