<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Tough decisions put Solich firmly in control of Cornhuskers
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ It has been two years since Tom Osborne handed
over the keys to a football program whose elite status is exceeded
only by that of the men who made Nebraska Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne and Bob Devaney were Cornhuskers legends. Frank Solich
was merely a name engraved on the head coach's office door; an
unproven coach facing a seemingly impossible task.
</P>
<P>
   He was scrutinized and criticized. He inherited what seemed to
be a lose-lose situation. And when the 1998 season unraveled into a
lose-lose-lose-lose situation _ an unheard-of 9-4 finish _ the long
shadows of the Cornhuskers legends dwarfed Solich.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach felt a lot of pressure,'' Nebraska senior rover Mike
Brown said. ``I think a lot of people doubted his ability as a
coach. That was totally unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   Only now, here at the Tostitos Fiesta Bowl, where maybe the
greatest of all the great Nebraska teams earned the 1995 national
championship, can Solich feel comfort and confidence that it's not
just his name engraved on the door of his office.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Solich has begun to carve his own legacy and he's done
it by making the kind of tough decisions that even caused Osborne
to hear criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Solich called a wayward player's bluff last September and the
bold, potentially season-crippling move bonded the team closer than
ever.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to know the biggest reason Nebraska stands 11-1
going into tonight's Fiesta Bowl showdown with Tennessee after last
season's debacle, go back to early in the season.
</P>
<P>
   It was a moment that contrasted similar moments when the
Cornhuskers were at their best under Osborne. Even the legendary
coach was questioned earlier this decade over how he handled
players such as former I-back Lawrence Phillips, whose off-field
troubles and attitude threatened to divide the team.
</P>
<P>
   When Solich faced a similar threat this year with I-back
DeAngelo Evans, whose complaints about playing time and bickering
with teammates sliced morale to pieces, Solich hammered his own
stake into the ground. Evans stormed into Solich's office
threatening to quit the team.
</P>
<P>
   Solich told Evans, fine. Quit. Leave. When Evans later asked to
return to the team, but refused to apologize to teammates, Solich
polled players and agonized over the call before deciding not to
allow Evans back. All it did was rally Nebraska players around the
coach and prove that this program no longer was Osborne's.
</P>
<P>
   It belonged to Solich.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some unfortunate things happen, but he showed our staff
and players what he stood for,'' Nebraska assistant Turner Gill
said. ``The thing I really admired was how he handled things not
only on the football field but in helping bring our team
together.''
</P>
<P>
   If a season can be defined in one moment, this Nebraska
resurgence is defined not on the field, but off it, where the coach
took charge last September.
</P>
<P>
   The Cornhuskers rattled off nine wins in 10 games after Evans
left the team and only got better when Solich made another tough
decision when he switched Bobby Newcombe from quarterback to
wingback, handing the starting quarterback job to Eric Crouch.
</P>
<P>
   Newcombe has since made it clear that he still would like to
play quarterback and Newcombe's father has gone public with his
disgust over Solich's move. But when the Cornhuskers line up today,
Newcombe will be at wingback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the small things are what can really make a difference
between having four losses and having one loss or no losses,''
Solich said. ``It can go the other way very easily. There are more
headaches (as head coach) but that's the way it is in any kind of
leadership role. As an assistant, you think you see things clearly.
But as a head coach, you have to make the final decision. You just
have to feel justified that you made the right call and move
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   It's becoming clear that when Osborne hand-picked Solich as his
successor he made the right call. With a win tonight, the
Cornhuskers likely will finish ranked No. 2 nationally, with a Big
12 championship and Solich finishing his first two seasons with 20
wins _ more than either Devaney or Osborne had in their first two
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things that are intangible are the things that make
Frank,'' Nebraska defensive coordinator Charlie McBride said.
``He's solid as a rock. He's loyal. He's a tough guy and he's not
going to sit and take anything. He's disciplined and his team shows
that discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Solich was given this prestigious,
pressure-packed job. But only now is it clear that the program
finally NO CARRIER
RING
CONNECT 8 &Cx1f; tat-z r nbx NT26  &QL; 
rsbx  &UR; NYTR-outback
</P>
<P>
   By Jody Royce NYT Regional Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   TAMPA _ The most famous version of ``The Drive'' happened 13
years ago when John Elway rallied Denver past Cleveland in the AFC
Championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, the University of Georgia used its own adaptation for
similar success.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs trailed Purdue by 25 points in the second quarter
but put together a 94-yard drive that forced overtime.
</P>
<P>
   They completed the biggest comeback in bowl history when Hap
Hines kicked a 21-yard field goal in overtime for a 28-25 win over
the Boilermakers in the 2000 Outback Bowl at Raymond James Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The largest previous comeback was 22 points, on two prior
occasions. Notre Dame, with Joe Montana at the helm, beat Houston
35-34 after trailing 34-12 in the fourth quarter of the 1979 Cotton
Bowl. A Jim McMahon-led Brigham Young squad made up a 35-13,
third-quarter deficit to beat Southern Methodist 46-45 in the 1980
Holiday Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs (8-4) got the ball with 7:28 left in the fourth
quarter after Purdue's Vinny Sutherland downed a punt at the 6.
Sophomore quarterback Quincy Carter then led the 'Dawgs on what he
called one of the best drives at Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   He hit tight end Jevaris Johnson for 23 yards, then Michael
Greer rambled 32 yards on a catch-and-run down to the Purdue 40.
Carter hit Randy McMichael, the other tight end, for 14 yards
before McMichael dropped a third-and-12 pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (tight ends) had made the plays all year,'' Carter said.
``When he dropped that one, I said, `Don't get your head down.
You'll make another play.'''
</P>
<P>
   After Georgia called its final timeout, Carter hit Terrence
Edwards on the next play for 21 yards on a crossing route.
Surprisingly, the Boilermakers (7-5) called timeout with the 'Dawgs
facing third-and-goal at the 8. Then Carter got a most fortuitous
bounce on the next play.
</P>
<P>
   Scrambling to his right, he threw back toward the middle. Purdue
safety Adrian Beasley knocked it off Willie Fells' shoulder pads to
McMichael, who snared it with 79 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   In the overtime, the Boilermakers went on offense first. After
moving the ball smoothly for most of the game, they stalled in
overtime. Travis Dorsch, who had a streak of 40 straight PATs
snapped on Purdue's second touchdown, was wide right on a 43-yard
try.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought our guys played hard for the most part,'' said
Purdue coach Joe Tiller. ``Little did we know how critical our
first missed extra point of the season was going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Runs of 10 and 9 yards by Patrick Pass ultimately led to Hines'
game-winning field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Dorsch missed two field goals in the second half. Each could
have rendered Georgia's comeback moot, but the Purdue sophomore
missed kicks from 40 and 38 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We drove the ball like we have all year,'' said Purdue
quarterback Drew Brees, named the game's most outstanding player
after completing 36 of 60 passes for 378 yards _ all Outback Bowl
records. ``We just didn't get any points out of it. This game
reminded everybody of the whole season and how it has gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Between the misses, Carter capped a 77-yard, eight-play drive by
running it in from the 8 with 4:33 left in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone talks about different QBs around the country,''
Donnan said. ``But nobody means any more to their team than Quincy
Carter does to our team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boilermakers' first three possessions ended with Brees
touchdown passes. The first two went to Chris Daniels, the senior
from Clearwater. The third scoring pass went to Sutherland with 63
seconds left. It came one play after a Purdue fumble was nullified
by an offsides penalty on the Bulldogs.
</P>
<P>
   On fourth-and-21, Purdue was forced to punt. Twice it was called
back for a penalty. On the third try, Greer returned it to the
Georgia 32, but fumbled it away.
</P>
<P>
   Brees tossed his fourth TD pass of the game on the next play. It
was a 32-yarder to Chris James; last year he played at Jesuit High,
about a mile from the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Boilermakers led 25-0 with 4:22 gone in the second, but
Georgia pulled out an option reverse, and reversed its fortunes
just 59 seconds after they appeared destined to lose.
</P>
<P>
   From the 26, Edwards took a pitch from Carter and galloped 74
yards to put the Bulldogs on the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the momentum back. We needed a big play and I just
happened to deliver,'' Edwards said. ``We hadn't had a chance to
run it, but coach Donnan called it at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   Brees was ready to drive Purdue to another score, but Georgia
junior cornerback Jamie Henderson intercepted a pass and returned
it 50 yards to the Purdue 40. He might have gone in for a touchdown
had Brees not tripped him up.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Bulldogs got a 32-yard field goal from Hines.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can have all those yards,'' Henderson said. ``We're the
ones walking out with a W and not an L.''
</P>
<P>
   Jody Royce is a sports writer for the Sarasota Herald-Tribune.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The HERALD TRIBUNE, SARASOTA, FLORIDA
</P>
</TEXT>
