<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-01 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4421 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC--SUGAR-VICK-HNS &LR;      01-01 1959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC--SUGAR-VICK-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Vick flashes skills galore
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JEROME SOLOMON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NEW ORLEANS _ Florida State coach Bobby Bowden says forget Y2K, V2K
should present more of a problem for the Seminoles.
</P>
<P>
   That's V2K as in Virginia Tech quarterback Michael Vick.
</P>
<P>
   According to Bowden, the talents Vick will display when the
country's two top-rated teams meet Tuesday in the Sugar Bowl are
not just special, they are revolutionary.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the quarterback of the future,'' Bowden said. ``In a few
years, Vicks will be running around everybody's campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he can do with the football is not something that can be
taught. There have always been guys who could run and there have
always been guys who can throw, but that complete package is not
very common. Especially when we're talking about not just a good
runner but a great one, and not just a good passer, but a very good
one with arm strength that ought to be outlawed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is so dangerous, we could know what play they are running,
defense it perfectly the way we want to, and he could do the
opposite of what the play calls for and make a big play. He is that
scary.''
</P>
<P>
   What is just as scary to Big East foes, who watched Vick claim
the league's Offensive Player of the Year honor, and other teams
around the country with national championship hopes over the next
few years, is that Vick is only a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   He has three more seasons to put his stamp on the game as Bowden
predicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a great compliment coming from one of the greatest
coaches ever,'' Vick said. ``It makes me think he really sees
something in me and he thinks I'm going to be a great player.
Hopefully, I will.''
</P>
<P>
   Vick has played quarterback since he began playing football at
age 7, but he had to be pushed into the position. His youth league
coach asked his team who wanted to play quarterback, and after a
few moments with no volunteers, a couple of teammates gave Vick a
shove in the back and a quarterback was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we had something pretty special when he was redshirting
last year,'' Virginia Tech offensive coordinator Rickey Bustle
said. ``He was as natural a quarterback as I have seen during
workouts, but I had no idea he would step right in and get the job
done as well as he has.''
</P>
<P>
   Bustle is not the only one surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``If before the season you had told me I was going to be invited
to the Heisman Trophy presentation, I would have said, `Yeah right,
tell me anything,''' Vick said. ``When they told me I was going I
was walking around campus in shock all that day. There's no way I
thought I would have this kind of success this season.''
</P>
<P>
   The success Vicks speaks of is an 11-0 run through the regular
season and a No. 2 ranking, with the national championship in
sight.
</P>
<P>
   Vick let it be known early this season what he had to offer,
rushing for three touchdowns, including a 54-yard run, in the
season opener against James Madison before leaving with an ankle
injury early in the second quarter. (He sat out the second game
with the same injury.)
</P>
<P>
   At times on the field, Vick looks smaller than his listed
measurements of 6-1, 212 pounds because of his uncanny ability to
make would-be tacklers miss. He scoots around like a puny return
man, but believe it, his chiseled frame carries the full 212-pound
load.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, his arm strength, which he said he honed while
throwing rocks and shells on the beach in his hometown of Newport
News, Va., is well above average. Toss in a quick release, quiet
leadership and poise under pressure, and you can see why Vick was
an Associated Press second team All-America selection.
</P>
<P>
   Vick led the country in pass efficiency, completing nearly 60
percent of his attempts with 12 touchdowns and only five
interceptions. He threw for 1,840 yards and averaged 20.4 yards per
completion for the Hokies' big-play offense.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Tech has 10 touchdowns this season that covered 50 or
more yards, and Vick's favorite target, Andre Davis, averages a
whopping 27.5 yards a catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the kind of arm that stretches a defense out,'' Florida
State defensive coordinator Mickey Andrews said. ``Their receivers
can't outrun his arm, no matter how fast they are.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Hokies do have a deadly vertical passing game, Vick is
even more dangerous on the option. He rushed for 585 yards this
season, averaged 5.4 yards a carry and scored eight touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just try to make plays any way I can, especially big
plays,'' said Vick, who was the first freshman invited to the
Heisman ceremony in 18 years. He finished third in the voting,
matching Herschel Walker's best-ever finish by a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   One thing Vick improved on as the season progressed was
accepting his mortality, realizing he couldn't make a spectacular
play every down.
</P>
<P>
   ``My decision making has gotten better,'' Vick said. ``In the
beginning of the season, I was out there trying to make a very big
play every play. Now I just let things happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``After you have two or three plays that don't gain any yards,
all you want to do is explode down the field, but I had to trust
that it would come and not try to force things.''
</P>
<P>
   Vick is not one to accept failure without quickly bouncing back,
and he can recall just one time being rattled in a football game _
when he opened the season and started his first varsity game as a
freshman in high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were out there killing me and I couldn't do anything,''
Vick said. ``I was about 4-for-20 for 34 yards. It was a good
learning experience for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The next question was if that game made him doubt himself and
his ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, because the next week I came back and passed fo NO CARRIER
RING
CONNECT 5 &Cx1f; tat-z r nbx NT26  &QL; 
rsbx  &UR; NYTR-citrgamer
By Mic Huber NYT Regional Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   ORLANDO _ Just when the Florida football team finally found the
offense that had been missing much of this season, the Gators
discovered it wasn't enough to overcome a couple of players they
long ago lost along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Plaxico Burress, who desperately wanted to be a Gator, yet
couldn't gain admission, and Paul Edinger, who grew up in Gator
land, but saw a better opportunity elsewhere, led Michigan State to
a 37-34 win over Florida Saturday here in the Florida Citrus Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Burress, a junior likely to be heading to the NFL, caught 13
passes for 185 yards and three touchdowns. Edinger, a senior from
Lakeland, kicked three field goals, including the game-winner as
time ran out, as the Spartans won in the head coaching debut of
Bobby Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The Gators' loss was their third straight, a first in the 10
years Steve Spurrier has been coach. It also ended a three-game
bowl winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   Just when the Gators rediscovered the pizzazz in their offense,
they ran into a team they couldn't slow down.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans made the most of their final possession of the game
to give Edinger the opportunity of a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the best feeling I've ever had in my life, beating the
Gators in my home place,'' said Edinger, who grew up about 50 miles
from the Citrus Bowl. ``You can't beat this. It's the best ever. I
just had to go out there and do a job, come back after a miss, and
I made it.''
</P>
<P>
   Edinger missed a 45-yarder earlier in the fourth quarter after
hitting a pair of field goals in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   He was perfect on a 39-yard kick as time ran out to touch off a
wild celebration by Michigan State players.
</P>
<P>
   The kick, coupled with Burress' heroics, ruined a high-powered
performance by the Florida offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like it is never good enough ... never good enough,''
shrugged Florida quarterback Doug Johnson, who ended his career by
completing 24 of 50 passes for 288 yards and three touchdown passes
to Travis Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the offensive outburst, the Gators lost their third game
in a row for the first time since 1988 and finished with their
worst record since going an identical 9-4 in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lost three in a row, we're 9-4. We're not going to be in
the top 10, we're not going to win 10 games this year,'' Spurrier
said. ``That's the way life is in 1999. I don't know what else to
tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gators finally got back to playing the type of football that
made the team one of the most exciting programs of the 1990s. That
turned into 367 yards of offense, but not enough to keep up with
the Spartans, who finished with 400.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our players played their hearts out,'' Spurrier said. ``I
don't think there was any give up in us. They hit a few more plays
than we did. That's about what you can say when they won by three
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously it was a game where both teams had chances to win
but they made a play or two more in the fourth quarter than we
did.''
</P>
<P>
   After getting just six first downs against Alabama in the SEC
Championship game, the Gators racked up 27 against Michigan State
and had three scoring drives of 80 yards or more.
</P>
<P>
   They did it by using formations and plays that had been missing
much of the season as the Gator offense ground almost to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a fun game to be a part of,'' Johnson said. ``We lost
but at least it wasn't a boring game. I had a lot of fun out there
today until the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a little more wide open this game than in the past. We
ran some trick plays, typical Florida offense. It was fun being
able to do that. At least we went out playing our kind of
football.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gators also went out fighting. Florida offensive lineman
Kenyatta Walker and Michigan State defensive end Hubert Thompson
were ejected for fighting at the end of a play in which Johnson
connected with Taylor for their third TD.
</P>
<P>
   On the ensuing kickoff, Florida's Demetrius Lewis was ejected
for shoving a Michigan State player.
</P>
<P>
   Florida was also penalized 10 times for 100 yards, including a
pair of unsportsmanlike penalties. One was called on safety
Marquand Manual when he ran around taunting Michigan State players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what was going on,'' Spurrier said. ``I'm
disappointed in some of our players. We haven't had that kind of
ruckus all year. It's sad it had to happen, sad some of our guys
were dancing around out there acting foolish.
</P>
<P>
   ``They watched the NFL guys do this and it's perfectly legal in
the NFL. They think they can do it, and you can't do that in
college. We thought we had coached them better but at times we had
too much dancin' and prancin' out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gators, who trailed 17-7 before leading 34-26, got a
bowl-record-tying three TD catches by Taylor, who caught 11 passes
for 136 yards. They also got a 1-yard TD run by Johnson and a
2-yard run by Robert Gillespie.
</P>
<P>
   The run by Gillespie gave the Gators the 34-26 lead with 13:27
left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans came back with a 30-yard scoring pass from Bill
Burke to Burress and a two-point conversion pass to Gari Scott to
tie the game at 34-34.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State then went 33 yards in six plays to give Edinger
his chance to be the hero. Edinger, who said a major reason he
chose Michigan State over Florida was because the Gators didn't put
a premium on field goals, drilled the one that broke a four-game
bowl losing streak for the Spartans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seems something always happens to the Gators,'' Johnson said.
``It was a weird year.''
</P>
<P>
   It also ended Johnson's career, one that never lived up to
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually a quarterback is remembered by his wins,'' Johnson
said, his voice trailing off. ``I know I wasn't the most successful
quarterback here but I did the best I could.''
</P>
<P>
   Mic Huber is a sports writer for the Sarasota Herald-Tribune.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The HERALD TRIBUNE, SARASOTA, FLORIDA
</P>
</TEXT>
